s><font color=#FFE081>Author</font></td><td valign=top background=http://www.elvenelite.com/images/cellpic3.gif class=headings><font color=#FFE081>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#BA9F70><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub12.ezboard.com/usommatilmouren.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Somma TilMouren</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Grand Moff</span><br>  Posts: 189<br> <font color=#F5F5DC>(8/31/01 2:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/felvenelitefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Backward Glances</span><hr size=1> &quot;Boy!  If your mother is through feeding you, you have a visitor.&quot;<br>
<br>
Somma excused himself from breakfast and went to meet the lean messenger.  He accepted the guild dispatches and slipped a few coins into the bard's pouch.  &quot;Thank you, Tarique.&quot;  With that, he was gone, the sound of his drum echoing through the Felwithe streets, receding through the early mist.<br>
<br>
Somma's father looked after the retreating figure until he was out of sight.  &quot;Barely in his teens.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;That's why they gave him the city run.  He'll be out ducking Sarnak like his brother soon enough.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, I suppose he will.  You only just arrived here last night, how did they know you'd be here?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah, the bards of Norrath move in mysterious ways.&quot;  Actually, Somma was quite familiar with the vast network of informants and contacts scattered across the land, having run mail regularly as a youth, anything to pick up a few extra coins.  He'd never learned to play an instrument though, and since one unfortunate expedition to Skyfire Mountains, supposed he never would.  &quot;No doubt they'll be chasing me across the Karanas tonight.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, I see you've already packed.&quot;  He eyed the stuffed satchels with some distaste.  &quot;One night is hardly a fair visit.  Your mother will take it out on me.&quot;<br>
<br>
Shannice's voice rose from the other room, like crystal chimes, lightly kissed by the wind.  &quot;I'll do nothing of the sort.  My son may come and go as he pleases and I will delight in both, knowing that his absence means only the promise of his joyous return.&quot;<br>
<br>
His father leaned in close and whispered conspiratorially in Somma's ear.  &quot;She'll take it out on me.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;It can't be helped.  I'll be heading west to link up with the Alliance scouring the countryside for some bandit.  I hear he's a very powerful monk, an odd calling to fall into banditry.&quot;<br>
<br>
The fog had begun to burn away and chimes rang once again from the sunlit kitchen.  &quot;No doubt you're protecting us from the whole truth once again.  The Karanas, I have heard tell of the Plaguebringer's influence there.  Will you need any special provisions or linaments?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah yes, the mighty Bertox.  Beware, lest he give you an itch.  Fear his power or risk a horrible sneeze.&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;You joke.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, I joke.  Callous of me.  The farmers do suffer terribly.&quot;  He did not mention the growing rumors of the Plaguebringer's influence in Ak'Anon to the south.  He moved quietly up behind his mother and massaged her shoulders.  The long hair that fell across his hands was a deep gold, only recently begun to develop the inevitable white streaks of age.  Her dress was a dark forest green, with lacework dating back centuries.  &quot;I shall require only Tunare's presence, and she is with me always.&quot;<br>
<br>
His father eyed the bag of dispatches meaningfully.  &quot;So, are you going to share the exploits of the mighty Elven Elite with your parents?  Or must we read everything in the paper like everyone else?&quot;<br>
<br>
Somma smiled and opened the bag, pulling from it a handful of notes.  &quot;Ah, some of this is old news.  The High Priestess Kiffe has joined us.  A very powerful addition.  Nalilya has acquired a pair of Efreeti Boots from an expedition into Nagafen's Lair, excellent.&quot;  His smile vanished and the color drained from his face, then returned again in an angry flush.  &quot;No.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What is it?&quot;  His mother clasped his wrist to steady him as he rose shaking from his seat.  &quot;What's wrong?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;This can't be.  It's impossible.  It must be false.&quot;  But he had never received false information from the bards.  &quot;They've killed the King of the Frogloks.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;In far Kunark?  Excellent news.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No, in Guk.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Guk?  But they're not evil.&quot;<br>
<br>
Somma crumpled the paper and flung it into the fireplace.  &quot;Tell that to my brothers.  The occasional skirmish or misunderstanding is to be expected.  After all, the frogloks have been forced into an odd web of alliances in order to defend themselves from the Trolls and undead which menace them.  And they consider an attack on their allies to be an attack upon them.  Who would not?<br>
<br>
&quot;These creatures, though we may consider them savage, allow the races of light to move freely through their city, attacking only to defend themselves or their allies.  How well we repay them for their forebearance.  It would appear we are now more driven by love of loot than the right.  Who is the true savage?<br>
<br>
&quot;This guild is not about the easy way, the most expedient path, loot and power above all - good, bad, or indifferent.  Elite is a set of standards with which to conduct our affairs among all the citizens of Norrath, whether they are incased in skin, scales or feathers.  We judge by actions, not by appearance.  The Elite in our title is not a measure of power.<br>
<br>
&quot;Father, we have murdered the sovereign of a non-belligerent civilization.  Tunare forgive us.&quot;<br>
<br>
Somma turned to his writing table and quickly wrote out a copy of his guild's charter, asking the members to read it again, not just the words, but the spirit behind them.  He grasped the elaborately etched pendant he had worn through thirty hard trials, never removed since presented to him by Master Colwyn and Sarnia so long ago.<br>
<br>
His father came to him quickly, reaching up to stay his hand.  &quot;And what do you think you're going to do with that?&quot;<br>
<br>
The look on his son's face was lost, possibly for the first time.  &quot;I just don't know.&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#F5F5DC>- </font><a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/belvenelite>Elven Elite</a><font color=#F5F5DC> - </font><a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/felvenelitefrm5>/Roleplay</a> <font color=#F5F5DC> - </font><a href="http://www.elvenelite.com">Elven Elite Home Page</a><font color=#F5F5DC> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.241b<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

